<p>Thank you for your continued support, especially during this time of political unrest in Haiti! The road to stability and an improved economy will not be an easy one, but we know that education and investing in the talented young minds that we see each day at Ecole Lâ€™Union are the keys to seeing positive change for years to come.</p>

<p>Recently, there has been a lot of information in the news about riots and aid workers leaving Haiti. Protests have left the country at a standstill. (Protestors have been demonstrating against government corruption, gas shortages, a devaluation of the national currency and a spike in prices for basic goods like rice.) Although some local protests have been observed, we have confirmed with friends and staff members at the school that the situation seen on the news in Port aux Prince is not similar to what has transpired in Cap Haitian thus far.</p>

<p>The majority of the public have been staying in their homes and all regular activities have been interrupted. As a result, the school doors have been closed since Feb 8th. While things have calmed down since last Sunday and some activities have slowly started up again, the feeling in the country is still very tense as people are unsure of what the future holds.</p>

<p>As we remain in contact with the staff at Ecole L'Union, know that they are just as anxious as we are to see the students back in class and taking steps towards brighter futures.</p>

<p>Thanks so much,</p>

